result.execSummary:
The defendant Warren Gavin Whitelightning was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case. One or more other charges in this case were dismissed. The dismissed charges were not proven and have no legal effect. Warren Gavin Whitelightning is presumed innocent of the dismissed charges.

  • Warren Gavin Whitelightning was found guilty of Battery, a class A misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 940.19(1).
  • Warren Gavin Whitelightning was found guilty of Resisting or Obstructing an Officer, a class A misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 946.41(1).

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

miscConds.notes:
The defendant must maintain/obtain full time employment/school that consists of at least 35 hrs/week.

When not full time employed/school, the defendant must apply for at least 3 jobs per week and report progress monthly to P&P with pertinent information in regards to applications.  The defendant must only apply for jobs qualified for - must accept any job offered - must not engage in any conduct that could result in the termination of his/her employment/school.

The defendant may not possess/consume any alcohol.

The defendant may not enter any bars/taverns.
The defendant must undergo an AODA assessment and follow thru with all recommendations.

records.addlTxt: Defendant Warren Gavin Whitelightning in court with attorney Mary L.R. Burns.  Defendant Warren Gavin Whitelightning in custody.  Jodie L. Bednar appeared for the State of Wisconsin. Called at 2:04 PM. State - resolved - G to #1 as alleged and G to #3 as alleged and dismiss #4, joint recommendation on #1 - probation, fine of $500.00 - inclusive of costs, free to argue jail time, #3 - costs, probation and free to argue for jail. Burns - 1 year probation with no jail. State - offers 2 years probation and no jail. Recess to discuss offer. Defendant is willing to agree to 2 years probation. Court questions defendant. Defendant still wishes to proceed. Defendant pleads NC to counts #1 and #3 as alleged. Court dismisses count #4 and #2 was previously dismissed. Court has plea questionnaire, goes thru it, finds the defendant has freely, voluntarily and intelligently waived his constitutional rights by entering his plea and right to JT, accepts plea, adjudges guilty, proceed to sentencing. State - follow joint recommendation. Burns - follow joint recommendation. Whitelightning withholds comment. Court sentences the defendant to the following: counts #1 and #3 - withhold sentence and place on probation for 2 years, concurrent to each other and consecutive to current jail term that he is serving - credit for 3 days only if revoked, with conditions as follows: count #1 - $500 fine - inclusive of costs - paid thru probation, #3 - costs only - paid thru probation, AODA and follow thru, no consumption or possession of alcohol and no entry into any taverns or bars, maintain/obtain full time employment with verbage, 50 hours of community service total - to be completed within the first 6 months of probation, right to appeal, adjourned. (send JOC to Dane County Jail)
